<DOC><DOCNO> AP880425-0229 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 0744EDT</FILEID><FIRST>a a BC-History Adv05   04-25 0562</FIRST><SECOND>BC-History, Adv05,0586</SECOND><NOTE>$adv 05</NOTE><NOTE>For Release Thursday, May 5</NOTE><HEAD>Today in History</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Today is Thursday, May 5, the 126th day of 1988. There are 240days left in the year.   Today's Highlight in History:   On May 5, 1961, astronaut Alan B. Shepard Jr. became America'sfirst space traveler when he made a 15-minute, suborbital flight ina capsule launched from Cape Canaveral, Fla.   On this date:   In 1494, during his second voyage to the New World, ChristopherColumbus first sighted Jamaica.   In 1818, the political philosopher Karl Marx was born in Prussia.   In 1821, Napoleon Bonaparte died in exile on the island of St.Helena.   In 1891, Carnegie Hall (originally named Music Hall) had itsopening night in New York, with a concert conducted by Peter IlyichTchaikovsky and Walter Damrosch.   In 1904, Cy Young pitched the American League's first perfectgame as the Boston Red Sox defeated the Philadelphia Athletics, 3-0.   In 1912, the first issue of the Soviet Communist Party newspaperPravda was published. (In the Soviet Union, where the old-stylecalendar was still in effect, the date was April 22.)   In 1920, Nicola Sacco and Bartolomeo Vanzetti were arrested andcharged with the murders of a shoe factory paymaster and guard inBraintree, Mass.   In 1925, John T. Scopes was arrested in Tennessee for teachingDarwin's theory of evolution.   In 1926, author Sinclair Lewis rejected the Pulitzer Prize forhis novel ``Arrowsmith,'' telling the selection committee in aletter that ``all prizes, like all titles, are dangerous.''   In 1942, sugar rationing began in the United States during WorldWar II.   In 1955, West Germany became a sovereign state.   In 1955, ``Damn Yankees,'' a musical about a man who sells hissoul to the Devil to help the Washington Senators win the AmericanLeague championship, opened on Broadway.   In 1980, a siege at the Iranian embassy in London ended asBritish commandos and police stormed the building. Three of theIranian Arab gunmen who had murdered two of their 21 hostages werethemselves killed.   In 1981, Irish Republican Army hunger-striker Bobby Sands diedat the Maze Prison in Northern Ireland during his 66th day withoutfood.   Ten years ago: In Italy, messages attributed to the Red Brigadessaid the guerrilla group was ``carrying out'' a death sentenceagainst kidnapped former premier Aldo Moro because the governmenthad refused to bargain for his life. (Moro's body was found May 9.)   Five years ago: An Eastern Airlines L-1011 carrying 172 peoplelost power in all three engines shortly after takeoff from Miami ona flight to the Bahamas. The pilot managed to restart the tailengine and return to Miami safely; it turned out that mechanics hadfailed to install oil seals in the engines, causing their failure.   One year ago: Former Air Force Maj. Gen. Richard V. Secord ledoff the congressional Iran-Contra hearings. The federal governmentbegan a yearlong amnesty program offering citizenship to illegalaliens who met certain conditions.   Today's Birthdays: Actress Alice Faye is 73. Actress Ann B.Davis is 62. Actress Pat Carroll is 61. Singer Tammy Wynette is 46.Comedian-actor Michael Palin is 45. Actor Jean-Pierre Leaud is 44.Actress Tina Yothers is 15.   Thought for Today: ``What you see is news, what you know isbackground, what you feel is opinion.'' _ Lester Markel, Americaneditor (1894-1977).</TEXT><NOTE>End Adv</NOTE></DOC>